n Analysis of “Rape” in Islamic Legal Discourse (1000– 1500 CE) -- tWITHIN THE HOME -- tBetween the Muslim State and Individual Agency: The Regulation of Sexuality in the Jewish Communities of Medieval Egypt -- tAttitudes to Domestic Violence in Christian Europe -- tEpilogue -- tIndex -- tThematic Indexes of Contents0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis reference work examines the ways in which some medieval behaviours and identities were categorized as criminal or deviant. It also explores the implications of modern demonization of the Middle Ages. As well as discussing constructions of deviance, this book also explores the behaviours and identities which provoked these labels and processes. The model is one of reciprocity between behaviours and processes of demonisation and criminalisation. Each authoritative essay engages carefully with this approach, examining behaviours, the ways they were demonized, and the relationship between the two processes. The three parts of the volume are centred around forms of discursive and normative power—religious ideologies, political ideologies, and legalism. The authors also explore issues of political discourse, spiritual censure, justice and punishment, and the construction of taboos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrimexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDeviant behaviorxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMedieval.  acrime.  adeviance.  aidentity.1 aBadr, Yasmine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennison, Amira K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Warren C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Sara M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb